<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFWitzel1999"><a href="/wiki/Michael_E._J._Witzel" title="Michael E. J. Witzel" class="mw-redirect">Witzel, Michael</a> (1999). "<a href="http://www.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com/ejvs0501/ejvs0501article.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com/ejvs0501/ejvs0501article.pdf" rel="nofollow">Substrate Languages in Old Indo-Aryan (<span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Ṛgvedic</span>, Middle and Late Vedic)</a>". <i>Electronic Journal of Vedic Studies</i> <b>5</b> (1)<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com/ejvs0501/ejvs0501article.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com/ejvs0501/ejvs0501article.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com/ejvs0501/ejvs0501article.pdf</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Substrate+Languages+in+Old+Indo-Aryan+%28%3Cspan+lang%3D%22sa-Latn%22+xml%3Alang%3D%22sa-Latn%22+title%3D%22International+Alphabet+of+Sanskrit+Transliteration%22++class%3D%22Unicode%22+style%3D%22white-space%3Anormal%3B+text-decoration%3A+none%22%3E%E1%B9%9Agvedic%3C%2Fspan%3E%2C+Middle+and+Late+Vedic%29&amp;rft.jtitle=Electronic+Journal+of+Vedic+Studies&amp;rft.aulast=Witzel&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft.au=Witzel%2C+Michael&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.volume=5&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ejvs.laurasianacademy.com%2Fejvs0501%2Fejvs0501article.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Indus_Valley_Civilization"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-masson-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-masson_9-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFMasson1842">Masson, Charles (1842). <a href="http://www.harappa.com/har/masson310.html" class="external text" title="http://www.harappa.com/har/masson310.html" rel="nofollow">"Chapter 2: Haripah"</a>. <i>Narrative of Various Journeys in Balochistan, Afghanistan and the Panjab; including a residence in those countries from 1826 to 1838</i>. London: Richard Bentley. pp.&#160;472.  "A long march preceded our arrival at Haripah, through jangal of the closest description.... When I joined the camp I found it in front of the village and ruinous brick castle. Behind us was a large circular mound, or eminence, and to the west was an irregular rocky height, crowned with the remains of buildings, in fragments of walls, with niches, after the eastern manner.... Tradition affirms the existence here of a city, so considerable that it extended to Chicha Watni, thirteen cosses distant, and that it was destroyed by a particular visitation of Providence, brought down by the lust and crimes of the sovereign."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Chapter+2%3A+Haripah&amp;rft.atitle=Narrative+of+Various+Journeys+in+Balochistan%2C+Afghanistan+and+the+Panjab%3B+including+a+residence+in+those+countries+from+1826+to+1838&amp;rft.aulast=Masson&amp;rft.aufirst=Charles&amp;rft.au=Masson%2C+Charles&amp;rft.date=1842&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B472&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Richard+Bentley&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Indus_Valley_Civilization"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> Note that the <a href="/wiki/Kos_(measure)" title="Kos (measure)">coss</a>, a measure of distance used from <a href="/wiki/Vedic" title="Vedic">Vedic period</a> to <a href="/wiki/Mughal_era" title="Mughal era">Mughal</a> times, is approximately 2&#160;miles (3.2&#160;km).</li>
<li id="cite_note-davreau-10">^ <a href="#cite_ref-davreau_10-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-davreau_10-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFDavreau.2C_Robert1976">Davreau, Robert (1976). "Indus Valley". in Reader's Digest. <i>World's Last Mysteries</i>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Indus+Valley&amp;rft.atitle=World%27s+Last+Mysteries&amp;rft.aulast=Davreau%2C+Robert&amp;rft.au=Davreau%2C+Robert&amp;rft.date=1976&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Indus_Valley_Civilization"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
